# Final Validation & Summary (Phase 16)

This is a formal module and runs after OpenRC configuration.

Checks:
1) users exist
2) shell paths are valid
3) `doas` or `sudo` works as configured
4) Git identity is configured for targeted users
5) SSH client setup works and GitHub SSH test passes when enabled
6) mount paths are accessible
7) clipboard helpers or file bridge function as configured
8) Phase 14 rendered aliases are loaded

Outputs:
1) success/fail per category
2) repair recommendations for failed checks
3) summary report written to `/var/lib/iosish/logs/install-summary.txt`

Validation behavior:
1) non-destructive by default
2) reads `/var/lib/iosish/state/` first
3) offers targeted repair mode for failed modules instead of rerunning everything
Canonical installer architecture (enforced)

Single ownership by concern:

| Concern         | Owner module          |
| --------------- | --------------------- |
| SSH keys        | SSH module            |
| Git identity    | Git module            |
| Aliases         | Global Aliases module |
| Mount paths     | iOS Mount module      |
| Clipboard logic | Clipboard module      |

Non-negotiable dependency graph:

```text
Preflight
  ↓
Users
  ↓
Privileges (doas/sudo)
  ↓
Filesystem layout
  ↓
Core packages
  ↓
Shells (install only)
  ↓
Aliases (registry only)
  ↓
Docs (man/mandoc)
  ↓
SSH
  ↓
Git (depends on SSH)
  ↓
Mounts
  ↓
Clipboard (depends on mounts)
  ↓
w3m
  ↓
Shell config rendering
  ↓
OpenRC
  ↓
Validation
```

State system (required for reruns):

```text
/var/lib/iosish/state/
```

Required state files:

```text
users.conf
shells.conf
packages.conf
features.conf
mounts.conf
```

Global registries layer (required):

```text
/var/lib/iosish/aliases.conf
/var/lib/iosish/env.conf
```

3-layer model:
1) State layer: user choices + module status
2) Registry layer: aliases/env/features
3) Renderer layer: shell configs/service configs

Shell module split (required):
1) Phase A: install shells and set defaults only
2) Phase B: render shell config very late using registries + detected tools

Global execution safety rules:
1) Every prompt supports `Skip and remember choice`
2) Every module supports `Apply to which users: root, primary, guest, multi-select`
3) Every write operation creates timestamped backups first
4) Every module is idempotent and repair-safe

Repair mode requirements:
1) allow rerunning individual modules without full reinstall
2) detect broken/missing config and offer targeted repair
3) read prior state before prompts, then default to remembered choices

Backup requirements:
1) before overwriting, create `*.bak.<timestamp>` copy
2) examples: `~/.bashrc.bak.<timestamp>`, `~/.zshrc.bak.<timestamp>`

iSH behavior requirements:
1) SSH server default is disabled; explicit confirmation is required
2) OpenRC is session-scoped in iSH, not a full persistent boot init
3) Mount module does not implement persistence; OpenRC may wire startup later

iSH TUI Setup

1) Quick setup (recommended defaults)
2) Guided setup
3) Manual module selection
4) Repair existing setup
5) Export setup report
6) Exit

